     * If we take a subsequence S only from these elements, then GCD(S) will be a multiple of p.
     * 
     * For GCD(S) to be exactly p, there must be at least one element in S whose value, after dividing by p, 
     * is not divisible by any prime factor shared by all other elements' (value/p).
     * 
     * A simpler approach based on the constraints:
     * 
     * If there are at least two or more elements in `nums` that are divisible by `p`, say $a$ and $b$, 
     * then the subsequence $\{a, b\}$ has length 2. Since $n \ge 2$, $2 \le n$. If $n>2$, the condition $|S|<n$ is met.
     * If $n=2$, $|S|<2$ means $|S|=1$. A subsequence of length 1, $\{a\}$, has GCD $a$. We need $a=p$.
     * 
     * Case 1: There exists an element $a$ in `nums` such that $a = p$.
     * If $n > 1$, the subsequence $\{a\}$ has GCD $p$ and length 1. Since $n \ge 2$, $1 < n$. This is a good subsequence.
